"If he was detained, the citizen would still be alive" does not logically imply "Judges who don't detain immigrants should be fired"Detaining an immigrant does not necessarily mean they will be deported, and not detaining them does not mean they will not be deported. The process is much more complex than that.Furthermore, the role of the judiciary is to uphold the law and protect individual rights, not to serve the political agenda of any one person or political party. Firing judges for political reasons would be a violation of the principle of separation of powers and the rule of law.It is important to remember that every individual has the right to due process and a fair trial, regardless of their immigration status. Deportation is a legal process that requires a hearing and a determination that the individual is removable under the law. It is not a simple matter of detaining someone and then deporting them.Additionally, it is important to recognize that the vast majority of immigrants, both documented and undocumented, are law-abiding members of society who contribute positively to their communities. It is essential that we treat all individuals with dignity and respect, and that we reject hate speech and divisive rhetoric that seeks to demonize entire groups of people based on
